{{Infobox person
| name = Sheila Helena Elizabeth Kitzinger
| image = Sheila_Kitzinger.jpg
| birth_date = 29 March 1929
| death_date = 11 April 2015
| known_for = Childbirth Campaigner, Author, Feminist
| children = Celia Kitzinger
}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}
{{Use British English|date=September 2011}}
'''Sheila Helena Elizabeth Kitzinger''' [[MBE]] (29 March 1929 – 11 April 2015) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[natural childbirth]] activist and author on [[childbirth]] and [[pregnancy]]. She wrote more than 20 books and had a worldwide reputation as a passionate and committed advocate for change. 

== Life and work ==
Kitzinger was born in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]]. She was a [[Social anthropology|social anthropologist]] specialising in pregnancy, childbirth and the parenting of babies and young children.  She campaigned for women to have the information they need to make choices about childbirth and was a well known advocate for breastfeeding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.breastfeedingnetwork.org.uk/sheila-kitzinger-1929-to-2015/|title=Sheila Kitzinger, 1929 to 2015 |publisher=The Breastfeeding Network|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> She joined the advisory board of the [[National Childbirth Trust]] (NCT) in 1958 as a teacher and trainer. 
[[File:Breastfeeding baby.jpg|thumb|A baby feeding.]]
[[File:Ameli's home birth.webm|thumb|A home birth.]]
She held academic posts at the [[University of Edinburgh]] and the [[Open University]],<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/apr/12/sheila-kitzinger|title=Sheila Kitzinger obituary|last=Hayman|first=Suzie|date=2015-04-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/pioneer-sheila-kitzinger-helped-women-reclaim-control-of-birth/news-story/51556dc3b28c97f7d1e60491c6da9793|title=Pioneer Sheila Kitzinger helped women reclaim control of birth|access-date=2017-08-22}}</ref> and was an honorary professor at the [[University of West London]], where she taught the MA in [[midwifery]] in the [[Wolfson School of Health Sciences]]. She also taught workshops on the social anthropology of birth and [[breastfeeding]]. She wrote many articles and books and was active in midwifery education in the UK and internationally.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.12968/bjom.2016.24.4.234 |title=A legacy from Sheila Kitzinger: Continuity of care is crucial |journal=British Journal of Midwifery |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=234 |year=2016 |last1=Page |first1=Lesley }}</ref> She lectured widely in the USA and Canada, the Caribbean, Israel, Australia, Latin America, South Africa and Japan and worked as a consultant to the International [[Childbirth Education Association]].  

She was a strong believer that all women who are not at high risk should be given the choice of a [[home birth]]. Her books cover women's experiences of [[breastfeeding]], antenatal care, birth plans, [[Induction (birth)|induction]] of labour, [[epidural]]s, [[episiotomy]], hospital care in childbirth, children's experiences of being present at birth and [[posttraumatic stress disorder|post traumatic stress]] following childbirth. Some of her writing was controversial for its time; ''The Good Birth Guide'' (1979) may have caused a rift in her relationship with the NCT<ref name=":1" /> and she was often at odds with radical feminist views.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/a-passion-for-birth-my-life-anthropology-family-and-feminism-by-sheila-kitzinger-book-review-10254467.html|title=A Passion for Birth: My Life, Anthropology, Family and Feminism, by Sheila Kitzinger, Book review |date=2015-05-16|work=The Independent|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-GB}}</ref>. Her work is considered influential in changing the culture in which women give birth<ref name=":0" /> She believed that: "Birth is a major life transition. It is – must be – also a political issue, in terms of the power of the medical system, how it exercises control over women and whether it enables them to make decisions about their own bodies and their babies."<ref name=":2" /> She was awarded an MBE in 1982 in recognition of her services to education for childbirth. 

In 1987 she made an extended appearance on television in the first series of [[Channel 4|Channel 4's]] ''[[After Dark (TV series)|After Dark]]''.<ref>See [http://www.openmedia.co.uk/afterdark1.htm production company website]</ref>

Kitzinger died  of cancer in Oxfordshire in 2015 after a short illness.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sheila Kitzinger 1929-2015|url=http://www.pinterandmartin.com/news/sheila-kitzinger-1929-2015.html|publisher=Pinter & Martin|accessdate=12 April 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150415002755/http://www.pinterandmartin.com/news/sheila-kitzinger-1929-2015.html|archivedate=15 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/medicine-obituaries/11530874/Sheila-Kitzinger-childbirth-expert-obituary.html|title=Sheila Kitzinger, childbirth expert - obituary|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-32277415|title=Sheila Kitzinger, natural childbirth expert, dies aged 86|date=2015-04-12|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-08-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> Her autobiography, ''A Passion for Birth: My Life: Anthropology, Family and Feminism'', was published shortly after her death.<ref name=":2" />  She has five children; her daughter [[Celia Kitzinger and Sue Wilkinson|Celia Kitzinger]] is a scholar and activist.

